segments.text: What other places were there at Northgate or anywhere else for Aggies to go and have a pretty good time?
We used to go to Lakeview Club.
Describe that.
That's out northeast of town.
Northeast of town, and it's just a hole in the wall.
You'd have that live band, and you could dance, and there was always dancing going on.
I mean, you could dance.
There was quite a few little places like that, but we'd go out there.
We could have our beer out there, but
It wasn't to excess.
I mean we'd bring back a few guys that liked to drink a lot, but most of us would have our two or three beers.
I mean we couldn't afford a lot of beer.
What time would you go from when to when?
We'd get out there about 9 o'clock and come back about 12, 30 or 1.
And you would wear what?
Blue jeans and a shirt.
I mean that was the, we didn't much change our dress.
Were there any well-known performers that you?
You know what, we went out there one time and saw ZZ Top.
They had a rock and roll weekend or something, and ZZ Top came up.
And they always had one or two country westerns, or every weekend was mostly country western, but I always wanted to go to the rock concerts.
You never could find any around College Station.
Brian, he had to go to Houston or Austin or somewhere.
Did you all do that much?
Yeah.
I had friends in Austin, so if I wanted a date I'd go over there and grab a ride with a guy from Austin, and we'd go over there and have a good time in Austin, and go to Dallas.
We used to go to the Houston Astros baseball games with Butch Gootsman every week.
And he was the loudest, most obnoxious fan that place had.
several years.
How did, did he get y'all tickets?
Yeah, he got us tickets.
He coached to get us tickets.
I mean we could pretty much go see the Astros any time we wanted to and not have to pay.
So that was a fun trip.
Mr. Rutter dies in the spring of 1970, your freshman year.
All right.
Then the next fall Jack Williams comes in.
Did that make any impression on you all at all?
Were you aware of that?
We did.
We weren't sure how he was going to take the place of Mr. Rutter.
I think he did a good job.
I mean, I think he took the legacy that Earl Rudder left and carried it through to fruition.
I mean, he made it work.
You are so correct.
He made, you know, and there was a lot of
We were in the protest era, okay?
Right there was all, you know, Vietnam War, everybody's protesting.
And, you know, there was a few people a few times, you know, us two percenters.
We were the liberals, okay?
Architecture students were the only liberals that campus knew.
All of us had longer hair.
I mean, we had, they considered us hippies and all this kind of stuff.
But, yeah, we, you know, there was a few times that we walked down, marched down to that Williams president, the president's house, and
had our signs and that kind of stuff.
I mean it wasn't a big deal.
It may have been 30 or 40 people as a whole, but it was just to be part of the culture at the time.
And it was never to degrade the university.
And we never got any press.
So it wasn't like we were doing anything that anybody wanted to know about.
But that was about the extent of the protest on that campus was the few
a few times, but I think that's what he did.
Yeah.
I have a speech I give fairly often that I call Camelot on the Brasses, using the Kennedy idea of Camelot at a special time, and my major point is only Earl Rudder could have done what he did.
only Jack Williams could have done what he did.
If they had been reversed chronologically, they both would have failed.
Rudder did what needed to be done, Williams built on it, and thank goodness for the effect of both.
Yeah, we, you know, when I got there, the non-rugs were still kind of outcasts.
I mean, we were still considered not Aggies, we were still considered, I mean,
The old army just did not like us.
They didn't, you know, they thought we were basically, and it literally did.
It separated the school.
It put one end of the student body on one end of campus and one end, you know, the rest of them on the other.
I think the greatest thing they did was put all the women down by the corps guys because all of a sudden all the non-regs wanted to go down to the corps dorms.
I mean, the female dorms, the co-ed dorms.
So I think they did it as well as any, and it could have been done, and I think,
I think it's basically also because we're Texans that it really  when all else fails, you're still a Texan.
So you're going to make it work one way or another, and I think that's why it works, and I think it's still why it works.
Let me give you  back to  you're a sophomore, and you're now on the varsity baseball team.
Describe the difference in being a varsity baseballer and a freshman baseballer.
Well, my sophomore year, they eliminated the freshman team.
So now we have freshmen on the varsity, which everybody that made it through that freshman year hate.
There's only about four of us left, four or five.
The rest of them, a lot of kids just did not come back.
They didn't want to tag.
They transferred.
So there's about five sophomores that moved on, which is about average.
And there's about nine or ten freshmen now.
They didn't have as many freshmen because they didn't have a freshman team.
So you just had, you know,
Coach Chandler brought about nine freshmen on.
So we have a split of about five, nine, eight or nine and then the rest are upperclassmen.
And there's not too many seniors.
There's only about three or four seniors.
And it's the same, I mean, if there's anything to be said for Tom Chandler, nothing changes with him.
It's the same.
So we knew the routine.
I mean, we knew what we needed to do in the fall, what we needed to get ready for.
We practiced probably, we have
six weeks of practice.
We probably practiced four weeks in the old cow barn because it rained every single day in the fall.
I mean my sophomore year.
I never thought it would stop raining.
So we had batting practice in there.
We dragged the cow down in there, the horse.
Now this is just across the tracks.
No, this was down next to the dairy, I mean the old creamery.
We called it the cow barn.
It was a
big barn that's now an administration building of some kind.
That's where we used to practice inside that.
It was dirt floor.
I mean that's really  Oh, are you talking about the old  right next to the library?
Yeah.
Oh, boy.
Anyway, we'll think of it later.
They converted it.
Yeah, yeah.
But they used to have dirt floor after they had all the horses and cattle.
The pavilion, right.
That's exactly what we called the cow barn.
So we'd go down there and practice, and we'd have to clean up all the cow stuff and have baseball practice.
Because there was no place where we could, we literally warmed up underneath the stands, underneath the cow field.
We loosened our arms up and then we'd run over there to take some grounders and do some, and we'd hit in a cage over there.
And that literally was fall ball, and then of course
It was getting harder for me because I was falling behind in architecture, which I didn't want to do.
My structures classes were hurting me and everything else.
So in the spring, I decided I'm going to give it one more try.
And I just could not keep up.
And I almost failed out of school.
That spring, I went in and talked to Tom.
And he says, I understand.
He says, you're making a wise decision.
You're welcome to stay in the dorm.
I have room for you.
We can keep you there.
He did everything possible for me.
I knew I couldn't stay in the dorm.
get an apartment, get a job, and so that's what I did.
I mean, that was a change in my life.
But you stayed with the team through the spring semester.
And we, you know, I think we won half our games.
I mean, it wasn't a great team.
And you were pitching.
I was still a pitcher.
Did you all make any important trip that you remember with the team that year?
We saw Tom Chandler get thrown out of three games in Tech at UT.
We had a triple header, we had to play two games on Saturday, or one game on Friday and two games on Saturday.
He got thrown out of every game.
It was a remarkable.
That's unusual.
Yeah, he was not happy that we did.
And I think we were pretty close to tied for the season with him.
And he really thought we got home town.
And most people don't remember that field where they had the big cliffs in center field and everybody's
They knew how to do it.
We didn't.
Of course, it was a long weekend.
It was a long ride home, I can tell you.
When you all went on an out-of-town trip, how did you go?
By bus.
And the whole team on the bus?
The whole team on the bus.
What did you all do on that bus?
Oh, listen to Tom Chandler tell stories, mostly.
The guys in the back would play cards and talk, but I was young.
I enjoyed it.
What stories about what?
All the old ball players.
He could tell stories about my brother and some of the guys that played with my brother.
He says one time they were going to a game and the bus broke down and my brother and
I can't remember his name, got out of the bus.
They couldn't wave anybody down to stop, so they went up the highway a little bit and pretended, when cars come in, they pretended they were pulling a cable across the road.
The car comes to a screeching halt, went off the road in the bar ditch, and of course,
My brother and his buddy are running back to the bus, and Tom Chandler's out there, what's going on?
What did you do?
Did you cause this person to?
No, Coach, we didn't do it.
We didn't do it.
But those are the kind of stories he would tell about the previous players.
And of course, he'd pick one or two guys that were on the team, and he'd start telling stories about the older guys and what they did and how they pitched the game.
He was an excellent, excellent storyteller, and that's really what I enjoyed on that couple trips.
So no mischief on the bus?
No, I mean, you know, a little bit of razzing.
You know, I had a couple of guys end up playing baseball in the back end with a sock and stuff like that, but nothing.
Where did you all stay on the road?
Usually at a Ramada Inn or whatever.
I can't even remember the place in Austin.
Was life pretty tame?
Oh, yeah.
I mean, we'd stay up until he'd come and not rap it on the doors.
What did you all know the rules really were about behavior?
Well, we all dressed right.
That was one thing, coat and tie.
We didn't touch the room.
We slept in the room and we took a bath in the room.
That was one of the rules.
He was not paying for any furniture or any TVs or anything like that.
And you really you took took you know, he made you take pride in who you were your Aggies and you know How did he how did he encourage that?

I think the older players and basically it just just like, you know, I'd say just like in the core But I mean the older guys say hey, this is what you do, you know, I mean he didn't have to do anything But you know the senior players you usually would would say hey, you know, this is what?
We're going here, we're going there.
They basically lead the team.
Did anybody say anything about hair length and mustaches?
Oh, absolutely.
There was none.
There was none.
You got a short haircut, no mustaches, no face hair, none of that.
You shaved every day.
You had a clean appearance.
Then at the end of that spring semester, you decide, or did you decide that spring?
I decided that spring about halfway through.
I knew I was not going to make two classes.
You know, I was not going to pass them.
So it was, I was skull pro that next year.
And you go, and you and Coach Chandler have a good chat.
Excellent chat.
He understands.
Did he give you any advice?
Yeah, he says I need to make class more often.
which he knew I was not.
So he says, if you just make your classes, you'll pass.
He says, but you don't make your classes, you're not going to go through.
So he says, you just got to make your classes.
So that was his advice.
What did mom and dad say?
My dad was convinced I was not going back to A&M.
He thought he would have a permanent employee there in El Paso.
And I went and talked to my counselor.
Was that Priestmeyer or somebody else?
This was in the architecture department.
I remember who it was.
I went in and I talked to them, and they said, no, well, you basically flunked out of school.
I said, you've got three passing classes and two playing classes, and the other grades aren't going to keep you in architecture.
I said, well, this is why.
I was playing baseball, all the situation.
They said, well, you need to take this class again, another class at summer school, take it.
He says, we'll put you on scholastic probation in the fall.
And I came back, and I got an apartment with a ballplayer who had finished out his eligibility, needed somebody to live with for a year.
And so I lived with him.
My grades went up, I started working, I got a job.
With whom?
Uh, D&B Oil Company, Dick Broach.
How did you locate that job?
Well, as I said, my brother was good friends with the Daces, which I became good friends with.
Oh, okay.
And they became good, they were good friends with Dick and Bill Broach, who had two young boys, and they needed kind of a permanent babysitter for two wild Indian kids.
And I was perfect, I was big, they knew I would not put up with it.
I babysat with him several times, and actually Bill said, would you like a job?
He says, would you be interested in working for us?
And I said, sure.
So I started working with their filling stations for a while, and then I started driving a tanker truck for them.
I was making good money driving a tanker truck.
About how many hours a week was that job?
Probably 20, 25 is all.
Do you remember what the pay was?
I got paid good money.
I was around $10 an hour.
because I was driving that tanker.
Oh, that was good money then.
Well, I was half of what you have to pay somebody else.
Yeah, but still.
He was getting a good deal.
No, I made, I was doing, I was okay.
I didn't need any money from my dad for spending, so.
You still didn't have a car?
I finally got a car.
My junior year I got a car.
In fact, my father-in-law financed the car, so I was able to afford it.
But you were not yet married?
I was not yet married to my future father-in-law.
He thought I needed a car.
And that young lady had stayed with you and she had put up with the  Oh, yeah.
She stuck around.
All right.
And so that junior year, how was it different from the first two years?
I was much more stable.
I was much more comfortable in the, you know, I was much more comfortable in an apartment.
I knew I didn't have the baseball over my head.
I didn't have to go work out.
The job was easier.
I worked all my life, so the job was easier to handle than baseball.
And I was getting more comfortable.
Larry Priesmeier and I had become pretty good friends, so I was much more comfortable, and he really guided me in what I needed to do to get out of college, and that's what his purpose was.
Now, when you got that car, you didn't play around much more.
No, I went to work and went home, went to school.
I mean, that's literally, I went to Austin a couple times.
I couldn't, you know, you really, I don't say you couldn't afford to, but
I enjoyed what I was doing.
We'd go to the lake, go to Somerville on the weekends with friends and go to the Lakeview Club once or twice a week.
I mean, I was happy with that.
It was very simple as far as
Did you ever go to one of the drinking parties at the clay pits?
Never did.
I keep looking.
Nobody that I know of.
Claims.
No, no.
Yeah, I went, but they don't remember exactly where it was.
Some were south and west.
During that time, while you were an undergraduate, were you aware of any secret fraternities at Texas A&M?
None.
Didn't know a thing.
Let's see, did you ever have, did you ever go to any of the big fancy dances on campus?
Never did.
Never had a date, I mean on campus.
The dates were always in Austin.
You didn't have any Tessie dates?
No.
Student indulgences, alcohol, what kind of alcohol?
Just beer.
What was the favorite brands?

Well, we used to drink Texas pride because it was the cheapest let alone star and then of course when I was when somebody else is buying I have a scotch, but usually it's you know, when you buy your own you have just a beer and What were people smoking?
Well with you know, that was when marijuana really got popular I mean and I never did it can actually say I never tried it
But the architecture department, it was very popular.
Now they were the liberals and they, you know, they- Did they buy it in Brazos County or did they bring it- They brought it with them usually.
From Houston- From their homes, you know, where they knew they could get it.
There was quite a few of the architecture students back then that smoked.
Was there any, did you all even know about anything like heroin or anything like that in the early 70s?
I did because I came from El Paso and in an environment of being in the border it was very easy to get access.
A lot of my friends accessed all that stuff.
I saw several of them die.
And that's why I like College Station and Bryan so well is I never saw any of that.
I never felt it around like I did in El Paso.
So I guess that's one of the things that attracted me to like it so much.
Were you aware that there were any dealers of any illegals?
No, not at all.
I don't think they would have lasted a day or two.
In your student days, could whiskey be bought legally in Brazos County?
I think so.
I thought it could be.
I can't remember buying beer and never being carded, because it was pretty much, I think it was 18 and 0, because they passed that law.
So I don't remember ever having a problem buying anything really to drink.
Did you ever hear anybody talk about going to the chicken ranch?
Oh, yeah.
In LaGrange?
Oh, yeah.
Really?
What did they say about the chicken ranch?
Well, my roommate used to go there probably once a month, the old ballpark.
And he'd get all excited because he had his money saved up and he could go over there.
And I'd catch him the next morning and go, oh, I met this new girl.
It was just, you know, he was funny.
He was quite a character.
Did the stories you heard from him, were they similar to the... Oh, the Alto, yeah.
I mean, half the baseball team regularly went over there.
So, yeah, and of course...
There were some guys from Austin that, of course, the people from Austin didn't go to LaGrange.
They went to Seeley.
LaGrange was for the Aggies.
But that's kind of the stories we heard.
And if on a Saturday night, if you and a group of friends were going to have a good time, you went out to the Lakeview Club.
Lakeview Club, mostly.
And at Northgate, was there anything else, North or Southgate?
None.
How often did you go to Houston?
Well, see, that was the difference, I think, in school now and school then.
I think everybody abandoned that campus and went to football games.
Nobody went to basketball games unless they were, you know, student athletes.
So most of the people went to Houston or Dallas.
In Dallas, everybody had to become a member of a club, you know, to drink.
So, you know, that was the, we'd go up there and join a club so we can go in and have dinner and drink.
But I think most of the drinking was done back at home for most of the students in the places they usually went to.
And I went to, you know, whoever took me, I went to their local,
you know, we're going to go to this club and dance and stuff.
In terms of student body, one of the items that I missed, integration, how were blacks treated?
The ones I knew were athletes.
You know, everybody was kind of treated equally.
Otherwise, I didn't, I mean, in the architecture department, there may have been one or two.
Everybody just kind of treated them the same.
I know there was some racist stuff going on at the time, some, you know,
what are they doing here, you know, that kind of stuff.
But it really, it was so minor and so limited that it was just an individual or two that created that kind of thing.
Did you go off campus much to shop, to buy clothes or anything else?
Oh, yeah.
I used to go, I mean, my favorite was to go downtown Bryan.
You know, that place was really pretty popular and we used to go down there to the shops and stores.
Where'd you go to the movie?
Well, the movie theater right there at Northgate was the campus.
And, of course, every Saturday night they had the stag films that we used to go to.
And how did Aggies behave during campus theater movies?
Oh, it was a riot.
I mean, every remark that could be made was made.
I mean, you couldn't insult anybody.
Nobody brought a date.
I mean, you're all just pretty much there.
entertaining on Thursday night or Wednesday night when they come out with the new movie.
I mean, everybody was just there to raise hell, so.
It was just the great remarks.
And your junior and senior years you, again, didn't go home except at the holiday time.
Right.
Do you remember any national or international event during your A&M years where you, it so startled you, you remember where you were when you heard the news?
Nothing like that?
Nothing like that.
It was, you know, the Vietnam War was gone.
It was startling everybody.
Nothing like September 11?
Nothing like that.
All right.
Vietnam.
How much did you and your buddies talk about that?
A lot, because a lot of them were gone.
I mean, my number was, I was the last year that they allowed college deferments, and my number was 76.
So, you know, if I didn't stay in school, I was going to be gone.
And, of course, all the guys in the Corps, we talked to them, and, you know, they're going to be,
they knew they were going to be going if the thing didn't come to an end real quick.
So it was some consternation there.
I mean everybody was.
What did you and your civilian student friends think about the corps?
I don't know.
Most of them admired them.
Most of them said, hey, I couldn't do that.
You know, most of them were, you know, these guys are hardcore.
Again, I'm from El Paso.
You have Fort Bliss.
I live two blocks from Fort Bliss.
I was around military every day, all day.
They were my school, you know.
So it wasn't that much different other than, for me, I don't think I could have handled the discipline.
I was too undisciplined and wasn't regimented.
I mean, I probably should have done it.
It would have probably been better for me to get me more organized.
The guys I knew
You know, they loved it.
They thought it was, you know, and they, you know, like I said, they'd come over to us to complain, but they always went back.
And you didn't, you and your buddies didn't necessarily look down on them.
It was just different than.
Oh, not at all.
We used to go watch them march.
We used to, you know, I mean, there was a lot of, I mean, there was, I don't know, five or six thousand in the Corps, and more than that, really eight, I think it was, when I was in my freshman year.
And we'd go over to, at the MSC, you know the, what's that field, I can't think of it.
The drill field.
The drill field.
Simpson.
Simpson.
And we'd all watch them march and we thought, man, that's, you know, that's a good bull.
I mean, we really did.
We enjoyed it.
We supported it.
You know, we were there, so.
Did you go to Aggie Muster while you were a student?
Never went to Aggie Muster.
But you went to, did you go to Yale practice?
Yeah, I went to Yale practice.
Every year, every game.
And you went to football games.
Actually, I worked, the first two years I was playing baseball, I went to the football games, and then I got a job with Coke, so I was down at the wood pasture, or whatever his name is.
You know, we'd service all the Coke machines and everything else.
So I was working the football and the basketball games.
I worked all of them.
What is it that pulls A&M people together?
What builds that spirit, that feeling?
I think we're all there for one purpose, to get that degree from Texas A&M.
I know I was there for that reason.
I admired my best friend's dad for what he had.
I never saw that from any other
you know, older people had college degrees.
They were never, let me show you this stuff about A&M.
Let me show you, I mean, you're always, you know, I don't want to say indoctrinated, but you're always in awe of how proud they were of the degree.
And I think, I think the old Army, you know, when everybody was in the Corps and had that camaraderie, I think it was, it was that that started it.
And I think now it's gone, you know, past that, like for me, I mean,
Look at the picture of my son.
He's two years old.
He's got boots on.
He's got Texas Aggies.
He applied to one school.
And I think that's what keeps people going back is because you don't look at anything else.
You want that for your son.
I mean, that's why I think it is.
It's such a family.
Like as I look on your wall, I see things that I think are very normal.
Yeah, see, Olsen Field, as a sidebar, if Tom was alive today, he'd tell you this.
He told this to my son and several people.
That was my fourth year architecture project.
Really?
Olsen Field.
Oh, talk about that.
I got with Coach Chandler.
I said, Coach, I got a project.
I need to do a project for my fourth year.
And I said, I want to do a new baseball stadium for A&M.
He said, we need a new stadium.
Oh, man.
He lit up.
He brought in two grass experts.
He brought in people from the Astros.
And Larry Priestmeyer helped me do this.
And like I said, I was a builder.
So we did schematics.
We did a four by four model with lights and all the baseball field.
I mean, it was literally, I wish I had my pictures of it.
I've lost them in the move.
That's what it was.
that design was almost identical to what they picked.
And we had it over a skylight, you know, had glass over it, and we, I presented it to my class and Dean Romnick and everything else, and of course.
Are you the one that came up with the idea that your project would be a baseball stadium?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
That's what I wanted to do.
I mean, I wanted to do it for Coach Chandler.
Now, where did you propose that it be located?
Exactly where it's located.
Okay.
I mean, it wasn't my idea.
It was Tom's idea.
He said, we need to put that thing, we need to start on the other side.
We want the baseball field on the other side of those railroad tracks.
And we want it to stand out.
We want it to be, you know, the, you know, and before it was just the old, there used to be the old riding stables was where that thing was.
So we presented it to our class in the architecture department and got an A on it.
And Tom helped a lot.
I mean, he really, his input was on that field.
He said, we need this and we need that.
We need these things over here.
So it was a complete facility, batting cages and pitching things.
And then we presented it to the Letterman's Association.
We took it to the Letterman's Association.
Tom said, you know, this is what we're presenting to you.
Oh, they loved it.
So let's put it in the lounge and let's sit it up there for the spring.
And so we put that thing in the Letterman's Lounge.
It stayed there until it got gray, I think,
green fabric got gray for the field.
And from what Tom tells me, Olsen walked in after one of the football games or something and said, what's this?
So this is the new, this is our idea of maybe doing a new football stadium, or a new baseball stadium.
He says, well, what's it going to cost?
And I had a complete bill, how much it was going to cost to build, and I had all the estimates and everything.
He says, well, I'll put up half if you put up half.
Do you remember what the number was at your estimate?
I can't even remember back then.
It was, you know, not over three or four million.
It was not in the numbers that it came in at, but it was significantly later that they really built it.
Right, and so the year you're designing it is 70?
And Mr. Olson indicates that he will make a big contribution about when?
A few years later, because that thing stayed in there a couple of years.
Okay.
So it was a couple of years later when he came in.
And the only condition, he said, there's only one condition, if you know the story, that I get to park my motorhome.
We're going to put motorhome slots over here, and I'm parking my motorhome right there for the football games.
That was the condition of part of the baseball stadium.
Where was Mr. Olson living then, do you know?
In Houston.
In Houston, okay.
He had not yet moved up to?
No.
His house just sold.
Do you remember where he lived due south of the campus?
Well, he lived about two blocks due south of the campus.
He went straight out by the President's house and kept going.
